        "id": "omMFTDZWdNcQ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Q1-What is the difference between \"Love\" and \"love\" in NLP?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "pv4AHtqydfQg"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "In Natural Language Processing (NLP), “Love” and “love” are considered different because of case sensitivity. A model may treat them as separate words, which can increase vocabulary size and reduce efficiency.\n",
        "To avoid this, most NLP systems use lowercasing (case normalization), converting “Love” to “love” so both are treated the same. However, in some cases like Named Entity Recognition (NER), capitalization can carry meaning, so it may be kept.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "tT8n846TdmTp"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Q2-What happens if stopwords are not removed?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "z7xGdVixdvPw"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "If stopwords are not removed in NLP, the text will contain many common but less meaningful words like “is”, “the”, “and”, etc.\n",
        "This can cause several problems:\n",
        "•\tThe model may focus on irrelevant words instead of important ones\n",
        "•\tVocabulary size increases, making processing slower\n",
        "•\tAccuracy decreases because useful patterns get hidden\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "mmcq8K5adz_L"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Q3-Provide two real-world scenarios where removing stopwords can be harmful."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "66KshoVod6P5"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Removing stopwords is not always good because sometimes they carry important meaning. Two real-world scenarios are:\n",
        "1. Sentiment Analysis\n",
        "In sentences like:\n",
        "•\t“I am not happy”\n",
        "The word “not” is often treated as a stopword, but removing it changes the meaning completely:\n",
        "•\t“I am happy” (wrong meaning)\n",
        "This leads to incorrect sentiment prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Legal or Medical Documents\n",
        "In legal or medical text, words like “not”, “no”, “without” are very important:\n",
        "•\t“The patient is not stable”\n",
        "•\t“This agreement is not valid”\n",
        "Removing these words can change the entire meaning of the sentence and lead to serious errors.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1uPDVPG5d9vJ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Q4-Explain the difference between stemming and lemmatization."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Ma3IEXw6eBxg"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Stemming and lemmatization are both techniques used in NLP to reduce words to their base form, but they work differently.\n",
        "Stemming is a simple and fast process that removes word endings (suffixes) to get the root form. It does not consider the actual meaning of the word, so the result may not be a real word.\n",
        "Example: “running” → “run”, “studies” → “studi”\n",
        "Lemmatization, on the other hand, is more advanced and uses vocabulary and grammar rules to convert a word into its correct base (dictionary) form. The output is always a meaningful word.\n",
        "Example: “running” → “run”, “better” → “good”\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DArapYvkdbZv"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Task 2: Build Advanced Preprocessing Function"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "QojwZJekeg7h"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import re\n",
        "\n",
        "def preprocess_text(text):\n",
        "    if not text:\n",
        "        return []\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Lowercase\n",
        "    text = text.lower()\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Remove URLs and emails\n",
        "    text = re.sub(r'http\\S+|www\\S+|https\\S+', '', text)\n",
        "    text = re.sub(r'\\S+@\\S+', '', text)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Remove numbers\n",
        "    text = re.sub(r'\\d+', '', text)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Handle repeated characters\n",
        "    text = re.sub(r'(.)\\1+', r'\\1', text)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Remove special characters/emojis\n",
        "    text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z\\s]', '', text)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Remove extra spaces\n",
        "    text = re.sub(r'\\s+', ' ', text).strip()\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Tokenization\n",
        "    tokens = text.split()\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Remove short words (except \"no\", \"not\")\n",
        "    tokens = [word for word in tokens if len(word) > 2 or word in ['no', 'not']]\n",
        "\n",
        "    return tokens"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "bA5_-9Q8eVw5"
      },
      "execution_count": 1,
      "outputs": []
